{"id": 225041256, "title": "Wimbledon 2024: dates, schedule, and ticket information", "text": "SW19 will soon welcome tennis players and enthusiasts from all over the world for another year of Wimbledon. The world\u2019s most renowned tennis grand slam promises to be particularly fascinating this year. Two-time champion and British hero Andy Murray could grace the All England Club for the final time after indicating he could retire in 2024. Cameron Norrie, Emma Raducanu, Katie Boulter, Jack Draper, Harriet Dart, and Dan Evans are among the other Brits set to appear at their home grand slam. Other intriguing storylines will be whether Carlos Alcaraz can defend the men\u2019s singles title he won spectacularly against six-time champion Novak Djokovic last July. However, another Spanish star, Rafael Nadal, looks set to miss the tournament in what could be his final year on the ATP Tour. Following his defeat in the French Open first round on Monday (May 27), the Spanish two-time Wimbledon champion said his \"main goal\" was to return to Roland Garros to play in the Paris Olympics. So when is Wimbledon 2024, what is the schedule, and can you still get tickets? Here\u2019s all you need to know. Wimbledon is from Monday, July 1 to Sunday, July 14. The middle Sunday will feature a full day of play once again after being introduced in 2022. Wimbledon qualifying takes place between Monday, June 24 and Thursday, June 27. Successful qualifiers will then enter the main draw. Here are the men\u2019s and women\u2019s singles schedules, which are subject to change due to the weather. You can read the full schedule (including doubles, wheelchair, and boys\u2019 and girls\u2019 events) here. Men's singles Women's singles A full order of play will be available the night before the next day\u2019s play. Unfortunately, the Wimbledon ballot for 2024 has already been held. However, tennis fans can join the early morning queue for a show court or ground pass access to all the outer courts.